                    <marginalia_text>
                        Iterum Consules: sed populares. Omnia Romana quasi in rota. Simplicia, composita, mixta. Nihil virtutis, aut vitij intentatum: scientia[e], aut opinionis 
                        incompertum. Sed pergo; statuiq[ue] omnes S.P.Q. Romani conclusiones experiri, seu politicas, seu patheticas. Illi vltro, citroq[ue] communicant: nos 
                        Lectores susq[ue], deq[ue] consultamus. Hoc fortassis interest, quòd nos principijs magis politicis nitimur; et ratione potiùs agimur, quàm appetitu agitamur. 
                        Illorum olim periculum: nostra nunc exercitatio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Iterum consules" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Consuls again, but of the people. The whole Roman constitution is rotating as it were. Simple, composed, mixed. No virtue or vice is left 
                untried, no knowledge or opinion unknown. But I continue and have decided to test all the conclusions of the Roman State, whether political or affective. 
                They discuss this way and that; we readers deliberate up and down. This is perhaps important: that we lean more on political principles, 
                and are driven more by reason than desire. What was once their danger is now our preparation.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
